Sep 14 2009 	Once again the Hard Rock comes thru with excellent service	I am a frequent guest at the Hard Rock ( about 7x/year), and we stay there because it's a fun crowd, great pool, and is much smaller than the behemoth hotels on the Strip. I have posted previous reviews, so this is just an update.Sometimes things go wrong with your trip. For me, the test is: what does the hotel do to make me happy and restore the situation? We had a problem with our reservation, but once I spoke to Laura, the evening manager, she quickly resolve the issue to our EXTREME satisfaction. We were treated as a valued customers, and I appreciate it.While we were there, the hotel had a fire. While this is something you don't often think about while on vacation, the HR's response was excellent - they quickly evacuated the hotel, gave us water while we waited in the parking lot, and everything returned to normal once the fire was extinguished. There is a lot of construction going on at the resort right now as they finish the second Tower addition and double the size of their pool. Since Las Vegas still has 100+ degree days, most of the work is being done at night, and yes, you can hear it. In general, the Hard Rock is a noisy place to stay, so if the party people scene doesn't work for you, I recommend Bellagio, where it is very peaceful. As for us, we keep going back to the Hard Rock.	
Sep 13 2009 	Great intro to Paradise Tower with some minor glitches	Booked the Paradise Tower via a 3rd party. Magic convention was in town and had a strong presence at this property. Valet and taxi lines seemed a little more slammed than in the past (I've probably stayed at Hard Rock 20 times) but my understanding is that this is a temporary situation.I was on 3rd floor with a pool/strip view. I was directly above where they are constructing the Euro pool . Small jack hammer and the like during the day but it wasn't a problem. A lot of what they were doing was landscape related.Room is similar in size to the Casino tower. Much darker color scheme, dark browns and black. An Ed Hardy look to the wallpaper and carpeting. Very dimly lit, there was no way you could read anything in the evenings unless you were in bed. The bedding was very comfortable and many pillows. Awesome flat screen TV.Due to the dark nature of the furniture, counters, etc. there is a lot of water spots and finger prints visible. Some days it took a long time of running the hot water until it turned hot. There is only a very large glass shower, no tub. The shower door lacks a gasket and despite my best efforts I always had a puddle of water on the floor after a shower. Those were the glitches.Paradise tower has an exclusive feel to it with security in its lobby 24/7 checking room keys. They have a couple of desk personnel in the morning so that you can check out without walking to the main front desk in the casino.The other glitch that comes to mind was on the Friday night they had both a Puddle of Mudd concert by the pool and a Santana Supernatural show in the Joint. The existing parking structure was at capacity and took a long time to empty out following each show.The first night there was a very loud music event for Magic by the pool and as another reviewer mentioned it went on until 1 AM. There was a country themed event the following night and it was not a problem and neither was the volume for Puddle of Mudd.Great service at Mr Lucky's, Pink Taco, and the pool (thanks Susan and Alex). Pool complex was fully open (only 1/2 open Spring 2008) and uncrowded.Very good visit. I think next time I'll book the Casino tower, it's more to my liking overall and I don't think the Paradise tower is worth the premium.	
