Aug 30 2009 	HRH 16 Aug to 21 Aug (Never again)	Due to the poor customer service at the Hard Rock Hotel on our trip in August 2008, I wrote a letter to make them aware of their shortcomings in customer service. Their response was to offer us a free night valid till September 2009. As we were always going to return to Las Vegas in August 2009, we took up the offer. We decided to stay a further four nights at the HRH instead of moving to another hotel as we had previously planned. I had advised the lady that offered the free night that we will be arriving at the HRH at 2.00pm after a 12 hour flight from New Zealand and a further hour or so flight from San Francisco. She said that she would put notes into the system but could not guarantee anything as check in on Sunday was 4.00pm.Sunday 16 August:Southwest flight out of SFO on time and arrived at the HRH at about 1.30pm. After standing in the registration line for about 35 minutes, when I get to the counter, the lady advises me that I should go next door to the VIP check in (things are looking up!!). Go to VIP check in, they take the usual credit card imprint and advise that they would call me when the room is ready.Lunch at Mr Lucky’s. Good meals and service (wife had cheeseburger sliders, I had the buffalo chicken).Wife goes to VIP check in to ask how much longer our room will be. She is rudely told that check in is at 4.00pm (3.45pm already). At 4.30pm both of us go to VIP check in. They tell me that the room is getting made up right as we speak. Get to the room at about 5.10pm. When we enter the room (540) we are overcome by a very strong paint smell. DW calls VIP desk to advise. They say that it is a VIP room and it has been freshly painted and the carpet cleaned. We had stayed in this room last year and it was not a VIP room then. When DW advises the desk of this, they tell her that as we had requested this room we should deal with it. When DW insists that there is no way that we can stay in the room as even in the very short time we have been there we are both getting headaches and sore throats, the lady advises that someone will be up with keys to another room. In the mean time a fruit platter is delivered to our room. The room service guy that delivered the platter agrees with us that the smell of paint is very strong. After 30 minutes when still no key has arrived, DW makes her way to the VIP desk. They insist that the key has been sent up and basically call her a liar. They give her keys to room 538. We move to 538. No smell of paint in the room except from what is coming out of our clothes. By this time I am on the phone to expedia to see if we can cancel the four nights we have booked after the free night. I hear loud knocking on the door of room 540. I open our door. The porter is here with the keys to room 538. I had trouble explaining to him that we don’t need keys to 538 as we are already in it. He was very rude and upset that his trip to the 5th floor was a wasted one. Lady from expedia heard the conversation and commented on the rudeness. To cut a long story short, we would have lost too much money cancelling the 4 nights that we had booked through expedia and as we had planned to only sleep a few hours per night we decided to remain at the HRH.As our flight out of Vegas was at 5.00pmon Friday, we decided to ask for a late checkout (extend to 1.00pm from 11.00am). On Thursday afternoon I ask the VIP desk for the possibility of a late check out. They tell me that I should check with the VIP desk on Friday morning.On Friday morning I visit the VIP desk to ask for check out at 1.00pm. You would think that after the problems that we had getting into our room that they would let us check out at 1.00pm. No, I was told that the room had to be vacated by midday. So much for VIP service!My wife and I have made 25 overseas trips in the last 3 and half years and stayed in over 30 hotels so feel that I am reasonably well qualified to comment on hotel customer service. We have never encountered such rude, poor and arrogant service at any other hotel. From what was once my favourite hotel, I can safely say that I will not be returning to the HRH in Las Vegas. I realise that the hotel may be wanting to project a “hip / edgy / rock star” image but feel that the staff have taken this too far and have started to behave like rock stars themselves and think that they are more important than guests. When I advised the lady that arranged the free night of the issues that we had at check in time and the fact that we had to wait so long for a room that was just not ready to have guests, her response was to offer us a free breakfast (which I refused). I will not be staying at the HRH again.	
