Jul 25 2009 	Uhhh... run down expensive and lackluster	Got to say... the Hard Rock Las Vegas is now resting on it's past performance and name alone. They are far, far from the best venue in Vegas no matter who you are or what you are looking for. I will acknowledge that there is something to be said for vintage, and worn but worthy performance (think 60's or 70's rock bands on revival tours). But that comes with age, mellowing, and non-stop attention to who the audience is and what is relevant to the time. Hard Rock LV has done none of that. They might continue to book some decent bands - but they need to be judged on more than a concert venue alone. The hotel is run down and lacks the personal attention to detail that can be found in other hotels. They give you no sense that you are anywhere more exciting than a Red Roof Inn. blah....blah....and more blah.. Dark, no sparkle (and I don't mean the rhine-stoney kind - just give me some vibrancy in the staff.....the energy level....something!) The only thing they have going for them is that they still seem to attract a young 20' something crowd that brings the energy and beauty (okay superficial beauty, but none the less it's something) to what is otherwise an unimpressive environment. The rooms are a huge dissapointment - just flat out nothing special. Dining = $$ and .....(yawn). A $13 charge for internet connection (complimentary at other hotels) - extra for guests at the pool ($20)/per - get over yourselves. Ya just ain't &quot;all that&quot;.Step your game up Hard Rock. We want more, and can (and did) find it for less. We checked out and went elsewhere.	
Jul 22 2009 	HRH is getting run down.	This past weekend was my 4th-5th stay at the HRH over the last 12 years and the only place I would normally stay in Vegas. I've always enjoyed staying there with the cool, laid back vibe. It was my 40th birthday and we got a great deal from Expedia for air from Detroit and 3 nights hotel for $550 each person. Usually whenever I looked at the HRH rates, they were way too pricey. I was excited to show my friends the hotel but right away I started to notice that the place was starting to feel tired and run down. The toilet paper holder was hanging in our bathroom, there were scuff marks on the ceiling, the paint in the hallways looked old, the poker machines at the center bar were filthy, etc, etc. Even the famous Hard Rock store was barren. Instead of the 20 or so tee shirts that made Hard Rock a household name, there may have been 5 selections and instead they were selling 20 kinds of jeans!! I was most surprised when I was sitting with my buddies at the center bar at 11:30 am and a group of 15 or so construction workers from the hotel sat down and started drinking. I know the bandana wearing, grunge look is &quot;rock and roll&quot; but with the orange safety vests, missing teeth and sweaty tees, we were kind of surprised to see them. One of my buddies thought it was strange that the hotel would let their employees - construction or otherwise - drink at the main bar. The place was still rocking every night but as for being a guest, I will probably stay elsewhere in the future.	
