Feb 2 2009 	The Hard Rock Rocked!!!	My husband and I just got back from Vegas. I have been there twice before and stayed at Treasure Island and The Venetian. By far, the Hard Rock was my favorite. All of the hotels on the strip are great but they are too overdone. We wanted a young atmosphere where people don't care what you wear, what you look like, etc. It was very laid back. The food at the Get Lucky 24/7 was awesome. It wasn't expensive. They serve so much food that my husband and I shared all our meals. The rooms were very clean and the bed was so comfortable that it was hard to get up every morning. The staff was very friendly and put us on the guest list every night for Wasted Space and Body English (just ask at the front). We will stay here again end of May because we loved it so much.	
Jan 31 2009 	Worst Casino in Vegas	For starters this is not a family friendly hotel. The lobby is a round room where the casino is and at night they will have stripper-esque women dancing with poles. I know it's Vegas but if you want to see a show like this you pay to go to one, you don't have to see it while you're gambling in the hotel lobby. The casino by the way, is tiny and underwhelming. They bring you drinks while you gamble which are very small and watered down and expect tips for every drink, so really you end up paying for what a regular drink would be somewhere else. I was there with my two best friends and husband and the worst part of our trip was waking up the morning after we got there. At about 5AM construction starts outside of our room. I mean literally outside of our room. I am laying in bed wondering where the hell all of that noise could be coming from, it sounded like someone was right outside our window with a jackhammer. I finally go to the window and open the blind and low and behold less than 30 feet from our window(which looked out on top of a part of the hotel) was tons of constructions workers with all kinds of tools making all kinds of noise. Right outside the window, literally. I tried to turn on my iPod and go back to sleep but by this time everyone in the room, two of which are the heaviest sleepers I know, are awake and annoyed. We call the front desk and tell them about the problem. Now thankfully they had a room at the opposite side of the hotel away from construction noise and we appreciate that but why on earth would you put any guests in a room where construction would be done 20 feet away from their window?! We had all unpacked our stuff and settled in and at 6AM had to pack up and switch rooms. I could still hear construction in the morning the rest of our stay from the other room but it couldn't be heard over an iPod. The rooms are disturbingly retro. Our first room was spacious enough but had no color and the bathroom was hidden by what looked like a dressing room's wall length three way mirror. Really odd. The beds were nice and the interior of the bathroom was okay. The rest of the room really needs some sort of color and decoration. The pool area was closed and the pools were drained while we were there but they looked like they would be pretty when open. I've stayed in Las Vegas three times in November (my husband always has to go there this time of the year) and the other three places I've stayed at have kept their outdoor pools open this late. I am one to lay out by the water even when it's 70 degrees outside.The food that the hotel serves is awful for what you would expect and what you pay. We ate at the Lucky's Diner a lot and the food was fried, greasy and expensive. The only meal I enjoyed here was tofu teriyaki and the ceasar salad. The last night we were there my girlfriends and I ate at Agu, the supposedly amazing Italian restaurant. We expected quality food for what we were willing to pay and were all extremely disappointed. Do not eat here. We did love Pink Taco however. We ate here everyday especially during happy hour. We loved the margaritas, the bean dip and the tacos. A few things I would recommend for this place. -Instead of paying for the high priced drinks run to the store across the street that sells liquor in it and make your own drinks in the room. There are also a bunch of cheap food places at the intersection the hotel is at. -If you can afford to, take a taxi to the strip instead of walking. While we were there major road reconstruction was taking place and we had to take a really long detour which on foot in a cute outfit, sucked. Also we didn't feel safe in the area. When we left the strip at night we paid a cab to take us home. Ladies especially do not walk by yourselves. -I have stayed at the Venetian right on the strip which is lovely. If you are looking to be away from the strip I would recommend the Red Rock Casino or the Green Valley Ranch. The last two have their own huge casinos, a theater, a great selection of restaurants and very modern rooms (with two flat screen tvs in every one). -The only restaurant in the hotel I would recommend is the Pink Taco.-If you are conservative, over the age of 25 or have a family than stay somewhere else.	
