Jun 30 2008 	Not for people with self-respect.	With its horrendous service and 'taxi ride' exile away from the main Vegas strip, it's a wonder the Hard Rock hasn't already collapsed under the weight of it's own pretentiousness. It was hard to figure out which was worse: the hotel staff, who can barely see the customer down the length of their own noses, or the hotel's typical, [--] clientele, where redeeming values were traded in for another pair of booty shorts. I'm pretty sure our single room had more character in it than the rest the hotel. Like every good vacation, the Hard Rock was truly a test of patience. If I'm ever tortured for information or sent to a concentration camp, I'll always have the Hard Rock as my glimmer of hope, since I'll always know there is at least one worse place I could be. When you've experienced the Hard Rock, things can only improve from there.At first glance, the facilities appeared satisfactory, but it was hard to get a clear interpretation since everything was draped in a haze of self-importance. It was like being on another planet, where world issues like the occupation of Iraq, rising energy prices, global warming and a slumping economy don't exist. For the customers of the Hard Rock, these issues probably don't. As long as my next shot is on the way and my pants retain their pleat, who gives a crap that people are starving to death from the price of corn?I've never before experienced an entire community of people who only care about stuff that doesn't matter. Even simple positive personal traits, like manners, are nonexistent. What do you call someone who values their 'good time' over the well-being of other people? Evil. If you're evil, you'll love the Hard Rock.If you want to see what exactly is wrong with the world, visit the Hard Rock.	
