Jan 25 2008 	Hard Rock Faces Tough Competition	As someone who travels to Las Vegas about six times a year on business, I am well-acquainted with many of the higher end hotels in the city. The Hotel at Mandalay Bay used to be a favorite before the Wynn opened up, and next month I'll be staying at the brand new Palazzo at the Venetian.In January of 2008, however, I found myself on a personal trip to meet my family. Not wanting to break the bank on &quot;my dime,&quot; I chose the Hard Rock. Five years ago, this was THE place to stay if you were visiting LV on a business trip and were between the ages of 21 and 35. The rooms were decent, but the restaurants and pool scene were great. The casino was small and kind of cozy--a rarity for Las Vegas.Well times have changed a lot over the past five years in Las Vegas, but the Hard Rock has stayed about the same. And it is finding itself facing stiff competition. The new tower that is under construction will probably be terrific, but in the meantime, here's some things to know.The room is okay. Some adjustments have been made, including a nice big flat-screen TV, but the newer hotels are so much nicer. Despite a carpet that needed to be cleaned or replaced, the room was clean and serviced well. The bedding was very comfortable. The bathroom was small but clean. There's no turn-down service here as there is in the nicer hotels, nor is there delivery of a morning newspaper. Mini-bar seemed nicely stocked, and the bathroom amenities were okay. Internet is $12.99/day.I didn't use the gym or spa this trip, but as I recall both are acceptable. I've actually had decent massages at the spa in the past. What's not acceptable is the $20 a day you're charged to run on a treadmill for a half hour. While that's not unusual for Vegas, you don't get access to a grand spa like the one at Madalay Bay. The spa here is small.Restaurants are great at the Hard Rock--from Starbucks and Mr. Lucky's (upscale diner) to Nobu (famous sushi) and Pink Taco (Mexican). I've never been to AJ's Steakhouse, but have heard good things. A new Italian restaurant has opened where Simon used to be.The casino is small, but has a fun vibe. If you're a serious gambler, there may not be enough options for you. I actually prefer to play blackjack there. I like the intimacy of the room.Here's my gripe. All guests are charged a daily $7.00 (plus tax) &quot;resort fee.&quot; This is not disclosed to you when a reservation is made. You are made aware of this charge at check-in. What this includes is criminal: free local phone calls and a shuttle to take you to the Strip. How ridiculous. In this age of cell phones, no one needs to use a hotel room phone, and you expect a hotel that is off of the famous Las Vegas Strip to provide transportation to it. It does not include access to the fitness center or free wireless. The charge is nothing but an attempt to nickel and dime guests. Why not simply quote a rate that is $7.00 higher? I threw a fit upon check-out and had the charges removed, but HRH should lose this deceptive charge from its business model.In short, you could do a lot worse than to stay at the Hard Rock. But you can also stay at hotels that are a lot nicer and are beginning to understand the value of good service and repeat business. Don't let the location dissuade you from staying at HRH. If you can get a decent rate and don't expect a lot of luxury, you probably won't be too disappointed.	
Jan 21 2008 	good place to party	I've stayed at the Hard Rock a bunch of times since college and have always had a good time. It's a few blocks off the strip and has a pretty young crowd. My wife and I stayed here because we decided to meet up with some family at the last minute and their hotel was booked and the Hard Rock had some pretty good rates over the weekend.The room has added a 42 inch plasma tv but for the most part it's pretty much the same hotel it's been for the past decade, with the multiple stains on the carpet as evidence. It's a party hotel and it's obvious that people treat it as such. I had some trouble sleeping because every few minutes this weird banging sound reverberated from the walls like someone was banging on the ceiling. Turns out the toilets have the strongest and loudest flushes on the planet because it sounded like we could hear every flush in the entire hotel. Strange phenomenon indeed. Also, the shower kept going off for no reason. Doesn't seem like the hotel is kept up very well. The bed was comfortable and we had a nice strip/pool view from the top floor. The pool is drained for the winter but for some reason we were still charged the $7/night resort fee. Luckily we got a great rate and it didn't matter all that much. But it still felt kinda odd.I'm trying not to slam the hotel all that much because it was always my favorite hotel but it seems like it's seen better days. Maybe I've grown up a bit and want more from a hotel. This kind of place is great if you're going with a bunch of guys/girls and want a great party hotel but maybe it's not the type of place I'll be going to in the future with my wife. We still had a good time but overall it could've been, and has been, a lot better.	
