Apr 23 2007	Another Room Theft! Poor handling by Hard Rock Staff	My husband stayed here recently on a business trip. And he too was told he was automatically upgraded to an executive suite (for no reason what-so-ever). Maybe that's the scam that Hard Rock staff is running since it's much easier for someone to break into the living area of your room while you are sleeping in the bedroom. Overnight, they stole his laptop, wedding ring, watch, $300 cash. They left his credit cards and I.D. (probably so they couldn't be traced with an easy get-away). There are NO cameras in the hallways at the Hard Rock, only in the elevators. My husband was told that was for the privacy of the guests, obviously not for their safety. I used to stay at the Hard Rock with my girlfriends at least once a year, but we will no longer stay there because we no longer feel safe. I'm glad more people are writing in to inform others. If you travel to any hotel, make sure you lock up all of your valuables and put the safety lock on your door when you are asleep!	
Apr 23 2007 	It's the Hard Rock what did you expect?	I should first start by saying, I'm a local. I live in Vegas, I'm 21, I party. If you're hoping the Hard Rock will be quiet, don't stay here. This hotel caters to ages 21-30, end of story. I stayed here with my best friend for one night to go to Body English Sunday School. I booked on the Hard Rock site and later received a promotion. I called and the reservation staff was super nice and willing to change my reservation to the promotion (even though it meant cancelling my original and rebooking me). I work in room reservations out here and this is NOT easy, it is NOT fun, and being nice about it is truly great service. I was not able to check into the room myself so I called and they added my friend to the room so she could check in, no problems. Her check-in was quick, when I arrived, I picked up my keys; the staff was friendly and courteous. We had dinner at Nobu and it was fantastic. The service was outstanding, the food was wonderful. Be warned: If you are going to Body English, check their event calendar first. I have been here twice (buy VIP passes if you can) and if there is a big event, no matter how important you might be, there is a great chance you won't get in. I was there the night of Paris Hilton's birthday party, people were not getting in after midnight without tipping the bouncers in the hundreds. The club is awesome, it's beautiful and the waitresses are hot! The music is kinda weird if you get there too early, but it gets normal once the club fills up. It's great people watching; I even ran into Frankie Muniz after the Grand Prix during one visit!The first night that my friend and I went in 12/2006 was the night of the big Christmas party that was being hosted by Ron Jeremy. On a Sunday night, it gets CRAZY. People WILL bring the party back upstairs so if you're hoping to get a good night sleep, don't stay here. It was loud, people would knock on our doors all night, it was crazy. This would really bug me anywhere else, but considering the price of the room and the clientele at this hotel, we didn't expect it to be quiet. My best suggestion would be to keep your expectations realistic. If you're going to one of the restaurants, try to make a reservation. If you're going to the clubs, BUY VIP passes (I know the VIP hosts and I still buy the passes just in case). Know what you're in for and you'll have a great time!	
