Apr 10 2007 	Rather Sedate Actually	Ours was a Sunday-Tuesday stay. We had all been to this Casino over the years, and one in our group had stayed in the hotel on a previous trip. We were aware of the atmosphere, and relative age of guests that would be staying here. Our group pretty much isn’t their target market. ; ) Parking – plentiful. We parked (free) in the covered parking structure each night. Check-in – Sunday late afternoon, plenty of staff, no line. Check in quick &amp; easy. Clerk confirmed we were NOT the oldest people staying at the hotel. Bless his heart. : ) Note, in the evenings when you go up to the elevators you must show your room key AND if you are carrying any bags they will ask what is in them. You are not allowed to bring alcohol purchased off site up to your rooms. HOWEVER, the elevators were not staffed during the day. Rooms – OK. WOW. Note, if you have tweens or younger, you may want to edit the Mini Bar section. Not sure they would need the position a day book. ; ) Beds are on a platform so while there’s not much give to them, they are comfortable. Linens were OK. The 42” plasma flat panel is almost too big for the room. I said ALMOST, (the rooms just a touch small, right?). Ample desk area and a small seating area near the windows. The black out curtains actually worked with no little rays of sunshine poking in to wake us up. (I hate when they don’t close all the way). Bathrooms … another WOW. Huge deep tub, rain shower head that even the tallest Bubba wouldn’t hit his head on. Good quality soaps &amp; lotions, plenty of towels. Liked the lighted mirror. Only downside, no vent to help clear the room after a steamy shower. Sound proofing wasn’t too great, as we could hear everyone in the hallways as well as people in the parking lots. Admittedly I’m a light sleeper, so I was armed with my earplugs. A non issue really.Pool – incredible pool atmosphere. Needed a wristband to gain entrance to the pool area. Music loud &amp; good in the pool area. If you’re not confident about how you look in a swimsuit, you might be intimidated here. Mr. Lucky’s – ate breakfast/lunch here one morning. Service good, people friendly, food reasonably priced and fresh. No complaints here. Casino – this was an absolute snoozer. I’d guess about a quarter of the tables were staffed. Slots had a good variety but were tight. For me, half the fun of Vegas is all the people in the casinos and lively tables. None to be had here. In the evening the place was nearly empty. Overall: I was advised this might not be the best place to stay with a couple of teenagers in tow, but have to say most of the caveats did not apply. Although it’s a young college crowd hanging out at the pools, and while I might not agree with some of the respect shown to women by some of the drunk guys (or lack there of), our teen travelers reported that no one really bothered them at all. In fact one was a bit miffed because someone called her 12 (meaning 12 years old, she’s 17). The valid complaint of staying here with Teens is that there is absolutely nothing for them to do. Our stay was during spring break, but early in the week. There really wasn’t a lot of activity going on at the Hotel. Seemed a bit sedate actually. If this hotel was on the Strip, it would have been totally perfect. But, it would have also probably cost considerably more than $80 a nite.	
Apr 9 2007 	Enjoyed NOT being a part of the gargantuplexes on the strip!	I was very skeptical about our upcoming stay after reading the bad reviews on the Hard Rock Hotel in Vegas ... most especially because we are a family with a 3.5 year old. Granted we were staying during the week, not a weekend (which I wouldn’t hesitate to do again), but I'm pleased to say that all went well.The pool was beautiful and awesome (mostly in size per capita) and I was surprised to see many other families with kids out there. As we were there during the week, there weren't numerous 20-30-somethings partying. Don't get me wrong, if our kid wasn't with us, I'd be out there partying with them (see Outrigger Waikiki on the Beach review) and I’m almost 40! I agree however, after viewing the Rehab-Sunday video ads around the hotel that kids are completely inappropriate at that venue and my kid is pretty cool (see attached photo with her playing guitar left-handed with Jimi Hendrix).We were staying with a relative that had VIP status with the hotel so that made things slightly smoother (check-in was private, the rooms were a little cheaper and we got a few rides in the hotel car) but it didn’t drastically change our opinion of the hotel. We were still regular people there and still had to pay $11.99 for internet access.We were put in a “mountain view” room (7th floor) and my husband promptly went down to ask if we could switch to the other side. He was told that it would be an additional $120 to switch to the “pool/strip view.” Mountain view it is! Turned out to be the best decision we made that week as it kept our daughter highly entertained watching all the airplanes land and take off from the airport both day and night. My initial concern was that we would hear a lot of noise from both the airport and the air conditioners. Other than 2 jets that sounded like they landed in the room next to us, we didn’t hear a thing. That includes people in the hallway too.As a parent, the Hard Rock Housekeeping gets 10 gold stars for getting a roll-away bed up to us in under 10 minutes at 2am! They even did it with a smile. Wow. That’s service. We stupidly thought our daughter could sleep in her blow-up, Nemo bed but when we got to the hotel, there was a hole in it (Nemo, not the hotel). Hence the roll-away. Hence housekeeping. Hence the 10 gold stars.The things I would change or complain about have nothing to do with the hotel and everything to do with Vegas ...the incessant SMOKING, the self-importance of people who think they are beautiful (especially when drunk) and the air of desperation for money where people will take advantage of you at every turn.While the hotel is definitely a cab ride from the strip, it was still a good time and I thoroughly enjoyed NOT being a part of the gargantuplexes on the strip!	
