Mar 13 2007 	Love the rooms - felt out of place in the casino	Company put me up in the Hard Rock last weekend. Plusses:1. The bed - featherbed with a down comforter - I was asleep in minutes.2. Amenities - 40-something inch plasma TV in the room, Bose Wave Radio, well stocked vanity.3. Surprisingly quiet - despite the party crowd that hangs out here, once you're in the room, you don't hear them. Maybe the people who hang out in the casino can't afford to stay in the hotel... and security is good about keeping non-guests out of the rest of the hotel.4. Mr. Lucky's remains my go-to restaurant in Vegas. When you want a good meal, fast, and without any BS, go straight to Mr. Lucky's inside the Hard Rock. The $7.77 steak and shrimp is still available (off menu) - just ask. It's not the biggest cut of meat you've ever seen, but it's plenty for me.5. Nobu is still my favorite for the expense account.6. If you have the time, you need to go to the pool. 'Nuff said.7. The curtains overlap each other in the room, so you can actually block out sunlight and get some sleep without having to use some clothespins or a clip hangar to close the curtains.Minuses:1. Proof of one of my laws of travel: the more you spend on the room, the more you get nickeled and dimed after you check in. Want to use your laptop for either wired or WiFi internet access? That's $11.95/day. Want to use the WebTV in the room? $5.99/two hours. I didn't bother to open the minibar.2. The rooms could use a little more light, especially by the closet.3. With all the college age hotties hanging out in the casino, I felt old the moment I walked into the place. Don't get me wrong - I don't like walking into a casino filled with blue-haired old ladies, either... but I felt a little out of place.4. Setting the alarm clock on the aforementioned Bose radio isn't very intuitive.	
