Nov 8 2006 	Beware the hidden charge!!	Beware the hidden charges!!! Everywhere you look they hit you.First the rate on the web looks good. Then when you check in and ONLY when you check in after you have signed the Early Checkout $75 payment agreement do they tell you that there are two $5 per night charges automatically added on. 1 for the resort fee and one a shuttle charge. I didn't even know they had a shuttle. Also the rooms have NO glasses in them, so if you want / need a drink of water to take a pill or are just thirsty you have to drink from the sink or open a $6.50 bottle of water. Nice touch. In addition they make you sign a statement that if you bring any food / water into the room they will charge $25 for it.The room is on par with any Holiday Inn in the country, but no Holiday Inn I have stayed in would put up with the stains on the carpet and furniture.Go to any one of the many other wonderful hotels in Vegas.. Avoid the Hard Rock.	
Nov 5 2006 	Fun Times At Hard Rock	I stayed at the Hard Rock Hotel in late October, 2006 from Thursday to Monday morning and had a pleasant experience. It is definitely a singles/ young adult hotel. I would say the target ages would be from 21-36. I have nothing bad to say about the hotel at all, it's not my favorite hotel in the world, but it definitely is a great party hotel. I went with a party of seven friends (including myself) and we were put in standard rooms next door to each other. Standard rooms aren't very big, but they're made for sleeping and they were clean and pleasant. The casino was a little smaller than I thought-- but had everything you needed. The pool was amazing, and if it was that good during the fall-- I can only imagine the summer. My favorite restaurant in the Hard Rock is Mr. Lucky's 24/7 which is a diner that is always open. The staff never gave me any problems and I did like it because it was in a world of it's own off the strip, but a very cheap, quick, and convenient cab ride to the strip. There are local stores and strip malls nearby when you need a dose of reality and not the Las Vegas glitz. I would probably stay in another hotel next time-- just to experience something different-- but I would NEVER turn down another stay in the Hard Rock because it was good. I would definitely stay there again though if I make repeat trips.	
Oct 22 2006	Love the Music the Food and the Casino	We didn't stay at the hotel, because we were on a budget, but we ended up at the Casino every night because of the wonderful food at the 24/7 restaurant. We loved the music, which included everything from 50's to present--and were left alone to play the penny slots or walk around as we wanted. Strangely enough, we didn't mind the music being loud because it was good. We were taken back when we noticed a group of young men walking around with what appeared to be a huge bottle of beer(?), until we realized that they were probably performers. Because of our schedule, we didn't get to go into any of the various shops--but they looked like something we'd have enjoyed. If for no other reason than the food (and the great waiters and waitresses), it's worth a visit. We noticed three older women who looked like they were out of place--sort of like they were expecting more &quot;action&quot; than anything--it was far more crowded on Friday and Saturday night, which was understandable, but it didn't appear to be a pick-up bar--although like anywhere, if you look for trouble, you can always find it. By far, our favorite Las Vegas restaurant and casino--and we saw several. If our budget allowed, we would have stayed at the hotel instead of across the street, but we were still easy walking distance.	
