Nov 28 2005	Why All the Fuss?	Having just returned from the Hard Rock Hotel for Thanksgiving weekend, I'm a little surprised at all the negative feedback I've been reading here. I've always enjoyed my visits to the Hard Rock but this was the first time I actually stayed at the hotel. Let me attempt to clear up some of the complaints. The unfortunate thing about these reviews is that a hotel can be unfairly criticized for issues that are out of its control. Vegas is a tremendously popular destination, especially on weekends. As a result, there will be lines at check in, waits at restaurants, etc. Also, stop complaining about the casino taking your money, because you lost your shirt has nothing to do with the quality of the hotel. My check-in just happened to be quick and pain free, but yes, the $5 resort fee is ridiculous and unnecessary. I've read many complaints about the rooms, most of which I found to be blown out of proportion. Our room was equipped with a flat screen tv, Bose Wave radio w/ cd player, digital safe, iron &amp; ironing board, &amp; web capabilities. There were various cd's in the room to listen to and rock n' roll photos throughout. The best feature in the room was the window/door that actually opened up to the outside. I know of no other major Vegas property that has fresh air access. One reviewer complained that the alarm clock was bolted down and that it somehow cheapened the feeling of the hotel. The 'alarm clock' in question was actually a $300 Bose Wave Radio so you can understand why they might bolt it down. The water pressure in the shower was poor but otherwise it was a clean, comfortable room. I think a lot of people who don't regularly travel to Vegas need to understand that it's only been in the last decade that the hotels have been creating standard rooms with luxury in mind. In the past, the idea in Vegas was the more time people are in the rooms the less time they'd be spending in the casinos, shops, restaurants, etc so they never put much emphasis on amenities. As the high end casinos become more and more competitive, they've had to seriously upgrade the quality of the rooms to keep their clients coming back. Unfortunately, the Hard Rock was completed just prior to the onset of this change in philosophy. Nonetheless, this is still one of my favorite Vegas properties. It is small and manageable and I fit right in with the target demographic (under 35, single, rock n' roll fan). I had another enjoyable weekend there and I will continue to make the Hard Rock a fixture on my future Vegas visits.	
Nov 13 2005	Warning: The Pool is CLOSED Nov.-March	We just returned from a stay at the Hard Rock Hotel and were very disappointed. We chose to stay there because of the fantastic pool, only to learn AFTER check-in that the pool is CLOSED mid-November through March. No one told us this when making the reservation, on the website or at check in. I don't believe the rate was reduced to reflect this major drawback. We were able to sit out by the pool, but there was no drink service, music, restrooms. Swimming was &quot;prohibited.&quot; This was especially disappointing since the weather was beautiful -- sunny and in the 70's. Several other guests we spoke to expressed the same disappointment, having also chosen the Hard Rock Hotel specifically for the pool.In spite of the the pool closure, they still wanted to charge us a $5 per day &quot;resort fee.&quot; C'mon, Hard Rock. You can't be serious!We checked into the Wynn for the remaining 2 nights and enjoyed the gorgeous pools all day long.	
Oct 31 2005	My loyalty is dwindling...	I've been staying at the Hard Rock since it opened 10 years ago. In the last few years, I've stayed there 2-3 times per year. I was at the 10 year anniversary weekend. Whenever someone asks me where I stay in Vegas, I enthusiastically say &quot;The Rock!&quot; But my enthusiasm is starting to wane.With the exception of a few select hotels in this world, most hotels have problems in one form or another. So my expectations are not unrealistic. And as a result, I've overlooked a few incidents I've had at the Rock over the years (such as the time we checked into our room and found food beneath the sheets). Because in general, the staff is friendly and responsive. And it's just a cool place to be.But problems are definitely starting to surface. The rooms are starting to look a bit worn down (and some of them have a very strange scent). I don't appreciate being told that there are no tables available at Body English one month in advance, while also being told that they don't reserve tables more than a week in advance. It also bothers me that I get no preferential treatment whatsoever when I know that I stay there more often than 95% of their guests and regularly spend $1000+ in the casino in a night. Each visit feels like the first time.And their website -----.But I do love the restaurants - Nobu is one of my favorites. I love AJ's - I've eaten there multiple times and have never had anything close to the bad experience described in another review on this site. I also like the Rock Spa and Brannon Salon. And the casino is one of my favorites in Vegas because it doesn't feel like you're gambling with 10,000 of your closest friends (or their kids). I've also always liked the Rock's location off the Strip, which creates an atmosphere that attracts more locals and young people from the Southwest, and less tourists or kids.So while I haven't officially written this off as my Vegas hotel of choice yet, I am shopping around for other options (and the Palms is not a viable option...don't get me started on that...). To start, I'm checking out THEHotel in a couple weeks. And I'm looking forward to the W Hotel that is supposed to open across the street from the Rock in a couple years. Bottomline - the Rock is no longer the only game in town when it comes to the young, hip crowd that is increasingly using Vegas as a weekend playground. The sooner they wake up to it, the better - afterall, this is the city that is constantly reinventing itself.	
Oct 31 2005	Great staff awesome music	My husband and I decided to stay at this hotel when we lucked onto a very good online deal through the hotel's web site. For $89 per night, it was worth every penny. The room was a good size, with the comfy bed, flatscreen TV, and French doors that opened being nice touches. The bathroom was a little small, but the shampoo and conditioner were good. We only had very minor problems -- no &quot;Do Not Disturb&quot; sign, very slow shower drain, shampoo and conditioner not replaced -- that we didn't find worthy of complaining about to management.Every staff member we encountered -- waitresses, front desk personnel, dealers -- were all very friendly and helpful. The common areas of the hotel look cool, the guests are all pretty young, and they play great music throughout the hotel. It's nice the hotel isn't huge because it wasn't too crowded. One caveat is that you have to have a car if you stay here -- it's way too far to walk to the strip and the shuttle only runs once an hour and stops at 7 p.m. We didn't play in the casino much because the blackjack rules favored the house a little too much for our tastes. The six deck games are no surrender, dealer hits soft 17, and most of the tables had continuous shufflings machines, which seemed to malfunction a lot. I was disappointed by the rules because the dealers, pit bosses and the great music made playing there fun.	
Oct 24 2005	The Hard Rock has gone downhill fast - STAY AWAY	The following is a copy of a letter I sent to the HRH after I received an email requesting a review of my stay. After the letter I have some additional info that you should read.Dear Mr Morton,Thank you for asking for my comments about my stay. I would like you to know that I travel frequently, I have visited over 20 countries, and I spend 20-30 days a year in hotels with three trips a year to Las Vegas and that this was my second stay at your establishment.I will tell you about my stay as events occurred chronologically. For starters, your online hotel reservations system is buggy. I made a reservation and for some reason it was automatically cancelled and re-reserved. I had to call to confirm my reservation. Also, I do not know why you do not include the $5 “resort fee” into the cost of the room. Am I going to be nickel and dimed at every turn? Is there an option of not paying the “resort fee”? If so, why was I not notified? What’s next, a bathroom fee? You could raise more revenue by requiring guests to place a quarter in the bathroom door. Is this a classy resort or a cheap motel?Upon arriving, the check-in line was short and I was able to get to a representative within 10 minutes of standing in line. The representative was professional, kind and courteous. Upon arriving in my room, I noticed that the carpet was still wet. While I appreciate that you shampoo your carpets, I feel you should wait until they dry before renting them out. It was somewhat uncomfortable to walk on it with bare feet. The carpet was a very cheap looking green/yellow and not the deep purple I remember from my last visit, but I suppose this is just a matter of taste - some people like the color of vomit.The bathroom was tiny, there was mold in the shower, the bar holding the curtain was rusted, the bowl was stained and the sink drained very, very slowly. Housekeeping did a great job cleaning the room and restocking towels and other supplies. I appreciate that there is a free room safe. I was impressed by the large flat screen TV in the room. One peculiarity of the TV is that once it was turned on, it became progressively louder and louder and the remote did not control the volume until it became uncomfortably loud. Also, reception on many channels was poor. Maybe you should include some aluminum foil and rabbit ear antenna so we can get better reception. My impression kept diminishing as I noticed that the alarm clock was bolted down. Do you really think we’re going to steal the alarm clock? I cannot remember the last time I stayed at a hotel that bolted things down to prevent them from being stolen. I’m starting to get the feel that this place is more of a cheap motel. I thought it was great that you have a refrigerator in the room, but I didn’t realize that it was sensors and that if you touch anything in there, you will get charged for it even if you put it right back. I know you don’t have a poker room even though on my last stay more than a year ago I was informed that a poker room was planned. This is understandable because poker is not very popular and no one likes to play (sarcasm intended). When I called the front desk to ask about the nearest casino with a poker room, I was misinformed that Terrible’s has one. I eagerly went there and found out that I was lied to and that they do not have a poker room. The next day at the pool was another disaster. At every hotel I have stayed at in every country in the world I was able to order drinks and food by the pool by just mentioning my room number and my last name. Not at your classy joint. There I was told that I would need either my ID or cash to purchase drinks. So, back to the room it was. Later, at about 4:15 I decided to order some food but the pool waitress informed me that the kitchen is closed. I’m sure you’ve done your accounting, but I was surprised that the kitchen would close so early considering the sun is still out until after 7pm this time of year. Oh well, your loss – I spent my money elsewhere.To top everything off, I clicked on the survey in this email and after I submitted it, I got a bunch of gibberish. Considering all else, this came as no surprise.As I mentioned earlier, I have visited Las Vegas many times and I have stayed at the Flamingo, Bally’s, Excalibur, Aladdin, Mirage, MGM, Stardust, Sahara, the Las Vegas Hilton and of course, the Hard Rock. I would recommend many of the hotels on this list, but certainly not yours. I’ll stay at the Palms next time.You can contact me if you need any clarifiacation.Sincerely,DELETED*****In my letter I forgot to mention that the ice machine on my floor did not work. After sending this letter, they were kind enough to mail me a form letter addressing a few of my concerns. It was clearly a cut-and-paste job they send to everyone who complains. One month after my stay I noticed that my credit card was charged again for one night. I called and the accounting department had no record of my card being charged again. I had to fax them a copy of my statement before the charges were reversed.	
Oct 19 2005	My Favorite Hotel in Vegas	My husband and I go to Vegas every year for a 3-4 day getaway. Each year we try to stay at the Hard Rock. We don't always make our reservations soon enough. This year we waited too long and could not get a reservation. We stayed at The Hotel at Mandalay Bay and loved it but we did miss the Hard Rock. The Hard Rock has great rooms, especially if you upgrade your room. The restaurants onsite are all good and some of them are great. The casino is not so huge that you need a cell phone to find your friends. The music is always great and the other guests are usually pretty cool. Each year we discuss if we want to try another hotel. We always decide to go back to the Hard Rock. This year we had to stay somewhere else and it was very nice but I look forward to next year and will try to make my reservation sooner. If you like huge, sprawling casinos, like the MGM, then this is not for you. We enjoy going out and seeing the sights but then coming back to the relatively small Hard Rock.	
