Aug 26 2005	The Hard Rock Rocks!	Having visited Vegas numerous times in the past &amp; had my hotel rooms paid for by my employer, I didn't quite care where I stayed, but each visit I made it a point to cross Koval Lane &amp; check out the Hard Rock. I did all my gambling there &amp; ate at Mr. Lucky's &amp; Pink Taco. I even made it out to the pool to take a look-which I'm not sure how I managed to gain access to at the time, not having a room key, which they checked each time on my recent visit-The pool is amazing, &amp; it was the reason I choose to book a room here on my vacation to Vegas.From 9am until 6pm I would just lay out in the sun by the pool &amp; order a Corona or dive in once I got too hot. The eye candy at the pool is truely amazing! Hot girls everywhere! It was like Spring Break in Cancun! And don't think that the pool is just someplace for celebrities &amp; models under 30, there was a wide array of different people hanging out at the pool when I was there. Families even, with kids. As long as you don't mind loud Rock music-which you can even hear underwater in a certain area of the pool-and feel comfortable in a Rock N' Roll, laid back atmosphere, then you'll fit in just fine at the Hard Rock. I for one, loved all the music they played at the pool, 95% of which seemed to fit into the &quot;Rock&quot; category, either Alternative, Hard Rock, 90's Grunge, 80's, or Classic Rock from the 60's &amp; 70's. I did hear a Dean Martin song one day, which was played right after the Scorpion's &quot;Rock You Like a Hurricane&quot;, an interesting segue.The rooms at the Hard Rock are equally awesome as the pool. Flat screen Phillips TV's in a large room with pictures of Jimi Hendrix &amp; Keith Richards on the wall, all decorated in a Nordic Minimalist style. One of the cool things about the TVs, is the muisc they pump in on several channels, as well as the Music DVD's they sceen on other channels. It was cool to watch old concert footage of Led Zeppelin on a huge flat screen TV when I came back to my room after gambling late one night! If youv'e read any of the other reviews, youv'e no doubt heard about the mini barrs in the rooms. The Front Desk staff are quick to point out that they are on motion sensors, &amp; you will be charged if you move anything, so be warned. But $5 for a Corona is not bad, only $.50 more than at the bars downstairs. Keep in mind that Vegas is just like New York or LA, everything is more expensive, just accept that, &amp; you will be prepared for your trip!A few other observations about the hotel; they will probably never have your room ready if you arrive before 2pm, I was on an early flight &amp; got there at 11am. They did give me a key so I could go hang out at the pool, though. Just somthing to keep in mind should you arrive as early as I did. The Sportsbook bar was very cool also. If you gamble at least a dollar per hand on the video machines in there, they'll comp your drinks, so at worst you'll have gambled for free for a half hour or 45 minutes &amp; paid for your drinks with the money you lost! Loved being able to watch like 8 baseball games at once, too! I'd love to be there during NFL season! Other cool things of note nearby are the Hofbrau House (German Beer Hall &amp; Restaurant) across the street, as well as a small market (white building, red lettered sign) that will sell you sun tan lotion, aloe vera gel, soda, &amp; almost anything else you could buy at the Hard Rock for half the price (suntan lotion @ Hard Rock=$10.95, at the market $5.95). You can probably buy beer there much cheaper, but you'd have to be discreet about bringing it back to the hotel, as that is strictly forbidden, &amp; they have security watching the elevators in the evening, so I guess if you must drink as cheap as possible, bring it in in the daytime! I prefer to get my drinks at the circle bar or the sportsbook bar though, especailly if you gamble, &amp; do well, they are pretty much free down there anyways! I did have 2 beers from the minibar, though. One right when I checked in &amp; another the last night after I finished gambling. Oh yeah, if stripclubs are your thing (bachelor parties, guys night out, etc), Club Paradise is also across the street, you can walk there versus paying $35 roundtrip cabfare to somewhere else. Decent club, although you will probably go through your winnings quickly!One thing is for certain after my last visit to the Hard Rock, I will never stay anywhere else in Vegas again! Awesome hotel for the under 40 crowd!	
Aug 23 2005	The Only Place I'll Ever Stay In Vegas In The Future	After checking out of the Mandalay Bay after one day because of an absolutely awful experience, the Hard Rock was AWESOME. The entire staff is friendly and eager to please, and overall the Resort and Casino was fantastic! Yes the overall crowd is young and out to have fun, but then again, this is VEGAS! As a middle-aged couple, we never felt too old - in fact it made us feel young again. And the music as expected, ROCKS.While not a mega-resort, all of the restaurants we dined in were superb, from cheap Mexican at the Pink Taco (fish tacos!), to sushi at Nobu, and the biggest find was Simon's, which was our favorite place to eat at the Hard Rock. Didn't have time to hit AJ's, but will be sure to do it next time.Pool does get crowded early, and better &quot;chair control&quot; would be helpful, by bouncing folks/towels off off chairs which have been vacant for an extended period of time. The murkiness other reviewers refer to is a sandy beach in certain parts of the pool, the water is crystal clear and if these folks had actually made it to the pool rather than looking out a window they would have noticed that. It would be great if the pool were larger, however. We were not there on a week-end, however I do suspect the Sunday Rehab party would be a bit much unless you were into the total party scene, then it is quite obvioulsy the place to be.The off-Strip location is a plus, it keeps the endless stream of passerby's away, so in general the crowd at the Resort and Casino is limited to people actually staying there, and there is a noticeable absence of strollers - I still don't understand all the strollers being pushed through Strip casinos. You won't find that at the Hard Rock. That alone is reason enough to stay here.I'm looking forward to our return...	
Aug 17 2005	Most fun in Vegas!	I stayed on a Sunday night just to experience &quot;Rehab&quot; at the pool - it was my first time at the Hard Rock (I usually stay at theHotel or the Mandalay). In a word: incredible! The Rehab beach party on Sunday is even better than advertised. The entire Hard Rock scene is not for everyone - only 25-35 year-olds who like to see and be seen will feel at home. The casino is very small and gambling seems to just be a by-product of people hanging out!Other than the eye-candy and great beach party, I was very impressed with my room. I only paid $100, but they gave me a huge two-room suite facing the pool area and strip (excellent views from only the 5th floor). The suite appeared to be about 800sf with 2 large TV's, double french doors and two mini-balconies, a wet bar and the best audio sound system in Vegas - complete with a receiver and high-end Klipsch subwoofer that, along with the separate main speakers, produced top-notch sounds. Perfect for a suite party. In fact, the Hard Rock is all about having a party...day and night!	
Aug 17 2005	Hard Rock the most sinful Casino!!	I have stayed at the Hard Rock many many times. I've stayed at quite a few Vegas hotels like Excaliber, NYNY, Tropicana, San Remo (soon to be Hooters Casino), the Orleans and the Palms. I don't know why I keep coming back to The Rock but I do. I love the pool and on Sundays they have a pool party called Rehab. I would not stay at the Hard Rock when the pool is not open, that's what they are known for...the pool. I would say the service at the Hard Rock is not all that great but they are known for that. And it's all good. It's a party house. From Body English the club(formally Baby's), the Joint (Beacher's Madhouse Comedy Show is great), to the circle bar. AJ's steakhouse is great....best shrimp cocktail and crabcakes in town. Like I said Rehab pool parties on Sundays is the bomb!!! Lots of eye candy for both men and women. It's worth taking a later flight back home or leave on a Monday. Rehab is open to the public but you would have to wait in long long lines (sometimes 3-4 hours on 3 day holidays). The Hard Rock is not a place where you want to get some sleep....um you're in Vegas....sleep when you get back home. You'll hear people crashing the symbols down the hall (there are drum symbols on the walls), to room parties to little naughty room action if you know what I mean. Don't be offended if you smell some strange cigarette smell down the halls. Like I said it's party house and don't bet on getting 1st class service. It does seem like half the OC are there on the weekends. You'll see a lot of fake boobs and lots of wanna-be Nick and Jessica's out there. You'll see a lot of whale tails (thongs that show when ladies sit) just walking around. There is a strip club across the street (Club Paradise) and some of the girls come to the circle bar after their shift to make some extra $$$. This is the most sinful casino in Vegas. It is off the strip and advise you not to walk especially in the Vegas heat. There is a shuttle that drops you off at MGM, Ceasars Forum shops, Fashion Mall. If you want to take a Taxi sometimes it would cost you a lot depends on where you want to go and how bad the traffic is. Best advice, if you can probably share a cab with someone going to another hotspot. Just yell out &quot;who's going to Drai's, anyone wanna share a cab to the Palms&quot; etc. Good way to meet up with some hotties that night. The taxi lines can get really long but they do move fairly quickly. I would try to find a taxi on the side of the casino then walk your way to the taxi line. Many taxi's drop off people on the side then you can grab that taxi. If you need some business work done or to print a a boarding pass for your flight, there is a kinko's nearby. I print out my boarding pass the morning I leave therefore I do not need to get to the airport 2 hours early. That's more time for me at the pool. Well hope this helps. I'll be back at the Rock labor day weekend!!!	
Aug 16 2005	A Motel 6 with a guitar on the wall	We decided to rent two rooms and request that they adjoin so my 13-year old stepson, my hubby, and I had extra space plus the joy of two bathrooms. When we checked in, the rooms weren't ready, so we left our luggage in one and told everyone we would happily visit the Cafe. One of the rooms had to have the carpets cleaned (eew...don't wanna know why), so when we returned we had the lovely smell of wet carpet. The mountain view rooms (which really is a view of the airport more than the mountains) looked a bit worn. Like too many parties had occurred. The rugs seemed washed out and faded. The purple satin comforters on the bed probably looked regal during the first few months, but are now pretty beat. Four pillows in white pillowcases finished the &quot;bedding,&quot; so it looked like dorm room decor. The mini-bar is completely sensored so I couldn't use if for my son's medicine (which had to be refrigerated). They told us we could rent a fridge for $25 a night. WHAT?!?!? That's just lame. We viewed the pool from one of the top floors, which had a tropical theme and COULD be great, but the water was murky. We went down to check it out, but it just looked dirty and uninviting. The whole place just seems to be neglected. We checked out after two hours. While the staff was amicable about not charging me $75 per room for canceling, they couldn't help but snidely add that they would be able to rent the rooms again to someone else that evening. I just smiled and said, &quot;I'm sure you will.&quot; Then, we skipped off to THE Hotel at Mandalay Bay and we were in heaven. (Read that review...awesome place that made our trip enjoyable!)Sorry, Hard Rock. Ya already need a facelift.	
