Feb 22 2005	Definitely Recommend Overall With Minor Caveats.....	I stayed at the Hard Rock this past Sunday night, which was over President's Day weekend. I am a late-30's financial exec from New York City.Pros: Extremely efficient check-in and check-out....smart, fast, courteous staff at the registration desk. Very good staff all around also, including casino dealers. Everyone seems on the ball and hard-working. I ate breakfast at Lucky's, and it was excellent. Hotel looks great inside and rooms were fantastic, except for the very iffy water pressure in the shower. Lots of great-looking women walking around. Room rate for a long-weekend night was extremely reasonable and the best I could find among the top on or off-strip hotels.Cons: The day I checked in, there was some sort of massive motorcycle rally/concert in the parking lot below my room. It was incredibly noisy, and I was on the top floor of the hotel. Add this to the brutally loud jetliner noise what seemed like right outside my window (the hotel is right next to the landing path of McCarran) and you've got a prescription for a major headache. I was on the &quot;mountain view&quot; side of the hotel, so I do not know if it would be different on the other side. Take earplugs if this bothers you, or I guess you might buy them there.Overall: I would stay again, but on the Strip side of the hotel since noise does bother me. I do think the hotel should note this issue on the website to inform guests before they make a reservation that it may be an issue for some. It is a tribute to the rest of the hotel that despite this, I enjoyed my stay and would go back.	
Feb 19 2005	Easy to navigate fun to explore	I stayed at the Hard Rock for four days in late May 2004. I very much enjoyed my stay and am planning to return in mid-April of this year. I'm 40-something, but I didn't feel out of place at the Hard Rock in the least. On the contrary, I felt welcome right from the time of check-in. I requested a room in the new tower because I had heard rumors that the bathrooms were better laid out and appointed there. There were two (2) queen-sized beds and they were probably the most comfortable beds that I have had in a hotel anywhere. I was on the mountain-view side of the hotel and could enjoy that view from an extremely comfortable chair. As others have noted, the pool area is beautiful (I found it even more attractive than the pool at Mandalay Bay) and the cocktail servers were always very pleasant. That made it very relaxing to hang out poolside and enjoy a drink while people watching.Hard Rock's casino is probably too small for serious gamblers. I didn't play tables there, but I did kill some time at the slots during the afternoons and had about as much luck on Hard Rock's slots as anywhere else, I suppose. I seem to recall that cocktail service was good, at least when at the times that I was around in the casino.For the record, I would mention that I've been to Las Vegas several times and have stayed in various hotels, including New York-New York, Treasure Island, Circus-Circus, Paris, and theHotel at Mandalay Bay. I wouldn't stay at Circus-Circus or New York-New York again, but Treasure Island would be a remote possibility. I liked theHotel at Mandalay Bay (and MB's pool is nice), but I wasn't awed by the place like so many seem to have been (I got an offer there at the time for $159/night but I question whether I would pay that for it again). The Paris is excellent and its casino is one of the most attractive in Las Vegas, but if you want an attractive pool scene, you won't find it at the Paris. Therefore, stick to the Paris during the cooler months.One final note: I wouldn't recommend Hard Rock for the first visit to Las Vegas. It would be wiser to stay on the strip for better access to explore the other casinos. I've been there and done that, though. I'll stay at the Hard Rock and enjoy a drink at the pool then gamble at the Paris and the other Caesars Palace-affiliated hotels and downtown. The rest of you hard-to-please 40-somethings can stay at theHotel at Mandalay Bay. Just don't come complaining to me about how hard it is to use MB's comps. Live and learn.See you in April Hard Rock!	
Feb 11 2005	Not Rock and Roll Heaven	We stayed here in March, 2004 to celebrate my daughters' 21st birthday. We attempted to check in around 1:00 p.m., but were told the room would not be ready for several hours. We walked across the street to the Hoffbrau House, and had a great meal served with authentic German beer on tap! Upon our return, we were told the room was still not ready, even though we arrived later than the estimate they had given us earlier. The front desk staff was rude, and the &quot;tude&quot; did not improve during the course of our stay. I definitely got the feeling we did not fit the target demographics for the hotel, and because we were a tad &quot;older&quot; (over 40)we were not welcome at the HRH.   When I questioned what the &quot;resort fee&quot; was for, I was told that it was for things like the pool (that was closed the whole time), the phone in the room, (gee, paying extra to have a phone?), and towels. HUH? Most hotels include these items in the daily rate. Not here.   The rock and roll decor, music, and even the elevators are great fun. We also enjoyed the size of the room, and the french doors that opened for fresh air. The noise from the low flying planes was a bit of an annoyance, at times, however. The beds were quite comfy, and the bathroom and toiletries were very nice.   The casino was energetic and fun, but we found the slots to be a bit tight. Yes, this place is definitely for the 20-somethings, and the center bar is one big meat market at night. We even experienced the &quot;joy&quot; of having college age kids falling down drunk around us, but have to say security was pretty good about keeping the drunks in line.   Overall, the Hard Rock Hotel was not a heavenly experience, but we do understand its' appeal to the masses. Even my daughter, who generally loves everything Hard Rock, found it to be elitist and unfriendly.   We are planning another trip to Vegas in May, and my 25 year old son wants to stay at the HRH for the pool, but &quot;the fogeys&quot; will be staying elsewhere. 	
